In C++, you can use `unordered_map` to store key-value pairs with fast access to individual elements. When you want to insert a new element into an `unordered_map` but only if the key does not already exist, you can use the `insert` member function which does not overwrite the value if the key is already present.

Here's an example of how to insert an element into an `unordered_map` only if the key is not already present:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_map>

int main() {
    std::unordered_map<int, std::string> myMap;

    // Key-value pair to insert
    int key = 1;
    std::string value = "One";

    // Using insert to add the key-value pair if the key does not exist
    auto result = myMap.insert({key, value});

    if (result.second) {
        std::cout << "Insertion successful. Key " << key << " added with value '" << value << "'." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Insertion failed. Key " << key << " already exists with value '" << result.first->second << "'." << std::endl;
    }

    // Trying to re-insert the same key with different value
    value = "New One";
    result = myMap.insert({key, value});

    if (result.second) {
        std::cout << "Insertion successful. Key " << key << " added with value '" << value << "'." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Insertion failed. Key " << key << " already exists with value '" << result.first->second << "'." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

The `insert` function returns a pair, with the first element being an iterator to either the newly inserted element or to the element that prevented the insertion (because it had the same key). The second element of the pair is a boolean value that is `true` if the insertion took place and `false` if it did not (because the key was already present).

In the above code, the first `insert` operation successfully adds the key-value pair to the map because the key is not yet present. The second `insert` attempt, however, fails to add the new value because the key is already in the map. The value associated with the key remains unchanged, demonstrating how `insert` does not overwrite existing keys.

