In Rust, you can use the `entry()` API with `or_insert()` or `or_insert_with()` to either get a reference to a value associated with a specific key in a HashMap or insert a default value if the key doesn't exist. In C++, you can achieve similar behavior using `std::map` or `std::unordered_map` with the `operator[]` or the `insert` method.

Here's how you can do something similar to Rust's `entry().or_insert()` in C++ with `std::unordered_map`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::unordered_map<std::string, int> myMap;

    std::string key = "example";

    // This will either return the existing value for 'key',
    // or it will insert a default-constructed value (zero for int) and return it.
    int& value = myMap[key];

    // You can then use 'value' as needed. If it was just inserted, it will be zero.
    // Increment the value (as an example of usage)
    value++;

    std::cout << key << ": " << value << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code will either fetch the current value associated with `key` if it exists or insert a default-constructed instance of the value type (`int`, in this case initialized to `0`) and then return a reference to the newly inserted value.

If you want to insert a non-default constructed value for the key if it doesn't exist, you can use the `insert` method combined with `std::piecewise_construct` and then check the boolean flag that indicates whether the insertion took place:

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::unordered_map<std::string, int> myMap;

    std::string key = "example";
    int defaultValue = 42; // Some non-default value

    // Attempt to insert the pair (key, defaultValue) into the map
    auto result = myMap.insert({key, defaultValue});

    // Get a reference to the existing or inserted value
    int& value = (result.first)->second;

    // Check if the insertion took place
    if (result.second) {
        std::cout << "Inserted default value for '" << key << "'." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Key '" << key << "' already existed with value " << value << "." << std::endl;
    }

    // You can now use 'value' knowing it's either the previously existing value
    // or you have inserted a new default value you wanted
    value++;

    std::cout << key << ": " << value << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Each of these techniques has a specific use case and should be chosen based on the desired behavior in your program.

In C++, you can use the `push_back` member function to add elements to the end of a `std::vector`. When you call `push_back`, the vector will automatically resize itself to accommodate the new element.

Here is an example of how to use `push_back` with a `std::vector`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> vec; // Declare a vector of integers

    // Push elements onto the vector
    vec.push_back(10);
    vec.push_back(20);
    vec.push_back(30);

    // Iterate over the vector and print out the elements
    for (int num : vec) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Output:
```
10 20 30
```

In this example, we create a `std::vector<int>` and then push three integers onto it using `push_back`. After the elements are added, we use a range-based for loop to iterate through the vector and print the elements.

For `std::vector` of class types, you can also use `emplace_back` to directly construct elements in place instead of copying or moving them, which can sometimes offer performance benefits:

```cpp
std::vector<std::string> words;
words.emplace_back("Hello");
words.emplace_back("World");
```

This is particularly useful for types that are expensive to copy or move, as it avoids the need for a separate temporary object.

Remember that when pushing back new elements, if the new size is greater than the current vector capacity, it will cause the vector to reallocate its internal storage to accommodate the new elements, which may involve copying or moving the existing elements to the new storage.

C++ does not have a standard container directly named `ordered_set`. However, a very similar standard container that behaves in an ordered fashion is `std::set`. The `std::set` container in C++ stores unique elements following a specific order determined by a comparison function (by default, `std::less<T>`).

To add elements to a `std::set`, you can use the `insert` member function. Here is an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <set>

int main() {
    std::set<int> mySet;

    // Insert elements into the set
    mySet.insert(10);
    mySet.insert(5);
    mySet.insert(15);

    // Iterate over the set and print the elements
    for (int elem : mySet) {
        std::cout << elem << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we are inserting integers into the `std::set<int>`, and the set will automatically order the elements. `std::set` is typically implemented as a binary search tree (often a red-black tree), which keeps the elements sorted as per a comparison criterion, ensuring that the insertion order does not matter; the elements will be in a sorted state when iterated over.

If you were referring to a third-party or custom implementation of an ordered set that is not part of the standard library, you would need to consult the appropriate documentation or source code for that specific container to see how to add elements. But for `std::set` and similar standard library containers (like `std::multiset`), `insert` is the typical method for adding new elements.
